When the fuck did we get tripcodes on /trash/? How long has it been like this?
Anyway, I just discovered Loka and I've been binging a bunch of her stories. As of now, though, I'm two chapters into Monster in the Closet, and I'm having a bit of a hard time getting through it. I dig the concept and there's tons of potential for interesting characters and conflict, but the second-to-second stuff is starting to grate on me. Since Tinfoil Anon was around last thread and we seem to share a propensity for including a bit of technical talk in stories, I figured I'd offer some feedback:

>Basic writing technicalities
Please, please, please type out the word "and". Use of the symbol is very jarring in both prose and dialogue in places where you don't see it in daily life, such as acting as a regular conjunction. I specify because there are situations in which you would use the symbol, namely as a part of a logo or "trademarked" name that features it. We expect to see the symbol in these contexts, so it is perfectly fine for your waifur to, say, frequent a store called Fluff & Fur and refer to it in the story as "Fluff & Fur", in dialogue and otherwise. Aside from that caveat, however, you should be typing out the word "and" in virtually every other imaginable situation.
Symbols aside the grammar isn't terrible, but could benefit significantly from closer attention to synonyms. I noticed several their/they're/there and you're/your mistakes, and they're not as easy to gloss over as you might think. If you use the possessive "your" somewhere you meant to use the contraction "You're", there's going to be a huge disconnect between what your reader expects from the sentence and what he actually gets. This will force a double-take to figure out what you meant, and disrupts sentence flow quite a bit. Take some time to edit; it'll pay off.

>cont

>Dialogue composition
Your characters have a habit of referring to each other by name in every single line. Sure, that makes it a bit clearer who's talking without resorting to dialogue tags, and kind of shit can get nigh-impossible once you're up to three characters. That said, the bitch is most people don't talk like that, and it's pretty distracting when everyone seems to. It's a reasonable verbal tick for a specific character, and actually might go a long way to demonstrating their personality through the action of the story, but you'd be hard pressed to find a group of three people who talk like that all the time. It takes me out of the story a little. I get the reluctance to use dialogue tags; I abhor them myself. There are better ways to try to get away without them, though, and sometimes it's better to just bite the bullet and use them. You have a lot of scenes with 3+ characters, so my advice would be to choose your battles when it comes to tags. If there's three or four people, maybe just use them. If you're dead set on avoiding them, my usual strategy is to lead lines of dialogue with descriptions of actions from the speaking character,

Ex:
"Have you seen my dog?"
The dragon shook her head.
"I'm sorry, I haven't.

>Characterization
Your characters are very odd. That's not a criticism; quite the contrary: I'm interested largely because they don't act how I would expect them to. That said, their mannerisms bear explaining and exploring. Forgive me if I'm mischaracterizing the story somewhat, as I'm not really clear on what tone you're shooting for (namely, how shitposty you intend the story to be), but take the biologist as an example. When we first meet him, he's acting like a college frat boy. Sure, he just got woken from a dead sleep, but discovering a literal alien tends to jolt one out of that kind of funk. Even before that, his treatment of the speaker seems unduly poor for someone with whom he shares a friendship. Basically, he doesn't act the way the average reader would expect a man of science to act in that kind of situation. I've known a couple of scientists and I know that isn't always the case. I am not suggesting he shouldn't act that way; in fact, he's a more interesting character for it. What I want to know is why he acts that way. It seems like he has some kind of personal history with the speaker that might lead him to act that way around him, and I would like to know what that history is. Maybe the behavior is from some other part of his personality. Maybe he's a drunkard, or just unusually rowdy or bitter. The important part is we need to know why he acts like that. You don't have to tell us all at once, but we need to know an explanation is coming. The speaker knows the guy, so surely he has a little insight he could pass on to the reader.

last one
>Technical subject matters
This is what really got me writing this post-chain. I get the impression you're in or perhaps studying the field, and looking to play subject matter knowledge into the story. This is by no means a bad idea. Authenticity can go a really long way. Simply sounding like you know what you're talking about helps the layman buy into things, and including details like that will pay double dividends when you run into other people who also know the subject matter. That said, it is a bit of a delicate problem. I won't purport to be any kind of master, but my Dare stories, Silver Lining, and Degeneracy Pressure are all full of that shit, and, to my knowledge, nobody has so far complained.

My biggest objection here is the links. Do not interrupt the prose and address to the reader to explain concepts to him, especially if you're going to send him somewhere else for that explanation. It's pretentious, insulting, and a huge obstacle to flow. It's literally better to say nothing and let us look it up. A more proactive, if a bit cliche approach would be to allow characters to explain concepts to each other. I did this a lot in Dare because the speaker was a layman and the technical character a geek trying to express affection to him in her own autistic terms. I had an excuse. You have easy excuses too. Take K-selection. The biologist observed small tits and assumed Loka was K-selected. Why not explain his reasoning? You could tell us how small tits got him to that conclusion, and what it actually means to be K-selected. Silver Lining was a bit different. Both main characters were subject matter knowledgeable, so instead, if I needed to explain something, I made sure it had some action in the story so I could "show" the reader what I meant. If I couldn't do that, I left the term/whatever out of the story entirely. For you, that might be something like a medical procedure. You don't have to teach us, you just have to be authentic.

Jumping in, you're pretty much saying the same things here I do as well.
The problem is that good and great dialogue can die if the reader doesn't like how it's tagged. I've gotten more than my share of shit for preferring action tags, and some people just plain prefer a bunch of saids.

When I stuck my foot in this a couple of threads ago regarding HATS^5, my general advice should have been to ignore tagging if you write dialogue first. Let the scene finish, then paint the actions and pacing in rather than try to think of everything in one pass.
Another point is to read aloud in the editing phase. One thing I tried on my last story was read only Character #1's lines, then #2. It gave me a much better feeling for separating people by speech patterns, and when they were mocking or agreeing based on mirroring the other.

You could have said this simpler. Then again, me and simple haven't been on speaking terms for at least a decade, so who am I to judge or joke?

One of the things I abhor is the "as you know" kind of infodumps.
Take a piece I shitcanned but will use somewhere later. What I wanted to know is if I could take nepetalactone (aka catnip) and make a stronger synthetic a la morphine/heroin. Guess what? The low-level research isn't going in the text. It's an iceberg.
Only deliver the relevant info. That way things you're really knowledgeable about can become genius bonuses (like you said), matters your OK with don't become nitpicks for the fanatics, and things you had to look up yourself don't become immersion breakers.

But the better way is to just remember to show. Leave the telling for the appendix in the backmatter.
